{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}} {{Other people|Friedrich Weber|Friedrich Weber (disambiguation){{!}}Friedrich Weber}}
{{Infobox person |name = Friedrich Weber |image = Bundesarchiv Bild 102-00344A, München, nach Hitler-Ludendorff Prozess.jpg |image_size = 250px |caption = Weber 2nd from left |birth_name = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1892|1|30|df=y}} |birth_place = [[Frankfurt am Main]] |death_date = {{Death date and age|1955|7|14|1892|1|30|df=y}} |death_place = [[Munich]] |death_cause = |resting_place = |criminal_charge = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources --> |criminal_penalty = |criminal_status = |party = [[Nazi Party]] |known_for = <!-- --> |occupation = |nationality = [[Germany|German]] |awards = |title = [[SS-Gruppenführer]] }}
'''Friedrich Weber''', Dr. (30 January 1892 &ndash; 19 July 1954) was an instructor in veterinary medicine at the [[University of Munich]]. In World War I he served in the [[Royal Bavarian 1st Heavy Cavalry Regiment "Prince Karl of Bavaria"]]. He was the leader of the [[Freikorps Oberland|Oberland League]] and ranked alongside [[Adolf Hitler]], [[Erich Ludendorff]], [[Ernst Röhm]] and [[Hermann Kriebel]] as one of the chief conspirators of the [[Beer Hall Putsch]] in November 1923. He was convicted along with [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler]] in 1925 but continued to head the [[Freikorps Oberland|Oberland League]] until 1929.
After his release from prison, he set up a private vet practice in Munich and continued close contact with [[Hitler]] being given a lucrative position in Berlin after Hitler's accession to power in 1933. He became an army vet late in [[World War II]]. After the war, he was heavily fined for war profiteering, but continued to practise veterinary medicine, eventually dying in reduced circumstances in 1954.
==See also== *[[Register of SS-Leaders in general’s rank#List SS-Gruppenführer|List SS-Gruppenführer]]
