{{Orphan|date=October 2014}}
'''Helen Elizabeth Haste''' (born March 17, 1943), also known as '''Helen Weinreich-Haste''', is a British [[social psychology|social]], [[developmental psychology|developmental]], and [[cultural psychology|cultural psychologist]] and a writer and broadcaster. She is a [[visiting professor]] in the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]].<ref name="Harvard bio">{{cite web | url=http://www.gse.harvard.edu/directory/faculty/faculty-detail/?fc=182&flt=h&sub=all | title=Harvard bio | accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref> She is an [[emeritus professor]] of [[psychology]] at the [[University of Bath]]. Haste also holds honorary visiting positions at the [[University of Exeter]], the [[Hong Kong Institute of Education]], and the [[University of Jinan]] China.
== Research == Haste's research focuses on young people's moral and political beliefs, and also on gender issues particularly in relation to science and culture. Her work on moral and political development and the civic engagement of young people has explored the factors that promote or inhibit participation in both conventional and unconventional forms of action. Haste is interested especially in how cultural narratives and metaphors are reflected in the development of young people's beliefs. Her work on science, society, and gender has explored the cultural images of science, how they reflect dominant models of rationality, how these are associated with conceptions of gender, and how they influence motivation to take up science interests. Alone or in collaboration with others she has worked on data from the UK, China, and South Africa. Haste is the author or editor of five books and over a hundred academic research paper and chapters. Books include ''The Sexual Metaphor'' ([[Harvard University Press]], 2004), ''Making Sense: the Child's Construction of the World'' (with Jerome Bruner: [[Routledge]] 1987), ''The Development of Political Understanding'' (with Judith Torney-Purta, [[Jossey-Bass]], 1992). She has also written numerous popular articles and has been a frequent broadcaster on British radio and television.
== Academic honours and service== Haste is a Fellow of the [[British Psychological Society]],<ref name="Fellow of British Psychological Society">{{cite web |url=http://www.bps.org.uk/bpssearchablelists/fellows?frmAction=showUser&Mem_MemberKeys_Selected=8309 |title=Fellow of British Psychological Socieity |accessdate=20 May 2014 |subscription=yes}}</ref> a Fellow of the [[Academy of Social Science]] and a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Arts]]. She is also an Honorary Fellow of the [[British Science Association]].<ref name="BSA fellowship">{{cite web|url=http://www.britishscienceassociation.org/about-british-science-association/our-organisation/honorary-fellows/current-honorary-fellows |title=BSA fellowship |date=2013 |accessdate=20 May 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725022608/http://www.britishscienceassociation.org/about-british-science-association/our-organisation/honorary-fellows/current-honorary-fellows |archivedate=25 July 2014 |df= }}</ref> She was president of the [[International Society of Political Psychology]] in 2002. Haste received the [[Nevitt Sanford]] award (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ispp.org/awards/sanford |title=Nevitt Sanford Award |publisher=International Society of Political Psychology}}</ref> and the Jeanne Knutson award (2009) from that organization for her contributions to the field of [[political psychology]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ispp.org/awards/Knutson |title=Awards & Recognitions |publisher=International Society of Political Psychology}}</ref> She received the Kuhmerker Award from the [[Association for Moral Education]] in 2011 for her lifelong contributions to [[moral education]]. For many years she was associated with the [[British Association for the Advancement of Science]] (now the British Science Association), serving as vice-president (2002-2008), chair of council (2002 -2004), and president of the Psychology Section in 1991.
From 2007-2013 Haste served as the chair of the [[editorial board]] of the ''[[Journal of Moral Education]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tandfonline.com/action/journalInformation?show=editorialBoard&journalCode=cjme20 |title=Editorial board |work=Journal of Moral Education |publisher=[[Routledge]]}}</ref> From 2010-2015 she was co-editor of the journal ''[[Political Psychology (journal)|Political Psychology]]''.<ref name="Political psychology co-editor">{{cite journal |journal=Political Psychology |title=Editorial board |doi=10.1111/(ISSN)1467-9221 }}</ref>
