{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2014}} {{BLP IMDb refimprove|date=January 2009}} {{Infobox writer | name = James Ursini | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1947|05|10}} | birth_place = [[Pittsburgh]], Pennsylvania, US | death_date = | death_place = | death_cause = | nationality = U.S. | other_names = | known_for = | years_active = 1973–present | occupation = {{Unbulleted list | Writer | Educator }} | education = {{Unbulleted list | [[Master's degree|M.A.]], [[Theater Arts]], [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] | Doctorate, Film, UCLA, 1975 }} | genre = Documentaries on [[Film noir]] }} '''James Ursini''' (born May 10, 1947) is an American writer living in Los Angeles, and an educator. He received his master's degree in [[Theater Arts]] and a Doctorate in Film in 1975 from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]]. He was born on May 10, 1947, in [[Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania]].<ref name="Ursini" /><ref name="IMDb" />
He has written and/or edited over a dozen books—most with [[Alain Silver]] and two with [[Dominique Mainon]] (''The Modern Amazons: Warrior Women On-Screen'' and ''Cinema of Obsession: Erotic Fixation and Love Gone Wrong in the Movies''). He is noted for his work on [[film noir]] with [[Alain Silver]] (''The Noir Style,'' ''The Film Noir Reader'' series, ''Film Noir,'' ''LA Noir,'' etc.) He has also done director studies on [[David Lean]], [[Robert Aldrich]], [[Preston Sturges]],<ref name="Ursini">{{cite book |title=The Famous Life & Times of Preston Sturges: An American Dreamer |last=Ursini |first=James |authorlink= |coauthors= |year=1973 |publisher=Curtis Books |location=New York |edition=mass market paperback |isbn= |page= |pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> and [[Roger Corman]] and numerous DVD commentaries for Warner Bros., 20th Century-Fox, and the Criterion Collection. He has also produced several features and short documentaries as well as appearing in documentaries on film noir.
